<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="217" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="27.[160,1156,379,683]" box="[160,276,379,405]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,276,379,405]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[160,1156,379,683]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">
<taxonomicName authority="Costa &amp; Duarte &amp; Iannuzzi &amp; Grossi, 2022" authorityName="Costa &amp; Duarte &amp; Iannuzzi &amp; Grossi" authorityYear="2022" box="[160,253,415,440]" class="Insecta" family="Scarabaeidae" genus="Tetragus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="217" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[160,253,415,440]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Tetragus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[259,362,415,440]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is separated from other Neotropical genera of Oryctini by the following combination of characters: males with nearly subrectangular body in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[1065,1155,449,474]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="8.[160,225,1685,1708]" captionTargetBox="[221,1093,152,1648]" captionTargetId="figure-3@8.[219,1097,142,1654]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 5. Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi, 1977). (a,b) Male habitus in dorsal and lateral views, respectively; (c,d) female habitus in dorsal and lateral views, respectively." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758329" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758329/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(b)); mandibles bidentate, with apical tooth broadly truncated at apex and larger than subapical tooth (
<figureCitation box="[353,447,519,544]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="10.[160,225,1156,1179]" captionTargetBox="[169,1149,148,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-156@10.[166,1149,142,1125]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 7. Right mandible in dorsal view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicate the apical tooth in (a–e), striate molar in (d)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758333/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 7</figureCitation>
(e)); maxillary galea wider at middle than basis, provided with strong scythe-shaped teeth on inner margin (
<figureCitation box="[672,765,553,578]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="11.[160,225,1161,1184]" captionTargetBox="[167,1127,143,1126]" captionTargetId="figure-61@11.[166,1149,142,1129]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 8. Right maxilla in ventral view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicating triangular galea in (a), elongate maxillary palpomere II in (b), lobed inner margin of galea and stipe with triangular lobe in (c), pointed and triangular teeth on galea in (d), scythe-shape d teeth and rounded inner margin of galea in (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758335" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758335/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 8</figureCitation>
(e)); pronotum bearing a deep and wide concavity in both sexes (
<figureCitation box="[490,592,588,613]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1146,1169]" captionTargetBox="[184,1146,142,1069]" captionTargetId="figure-59@12.[166,1149,142,1114]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 9. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of males in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii (Endrödi); (b) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (c) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (d) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758337" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758337/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figures 9</figureCitation>
(d) and 
<figureCitation box="[674,787,588,613]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="14.[160,225,1441,1464]" captionTargetBox="[168,1146,144,1407]" captionTargetId="figure-42@14.[166,1149,142,1410]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 11. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of females in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi;(b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedi sp.nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Arrow indicates punctate frons in (b)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758341" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758341/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figures 11</figureCitation>
(e)); elytral surface with deep and ocellate punctures; protibiae with 4 short teeth on outer margin (
<figureCitation box="[921,1017,623,648]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1146,1169]" captionTargetBox="[184,1146,142,1069]" captionTargetId="figure-59@12.[166,1149,142,1114]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 9. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of males in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii (Endrödi); (b) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (c) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (d) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758337" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758337/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 9</figureCitation>
(d)); ventrite V about 1.5 times longer than ventrite VI in female (
<figureCitation box="[747,854,658,683]" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="16.[160,225,1058,1081]" captionTargetBox="[166,1146,145,1023]" captionTargetId="figure-155@16.[166,1149,142,1026]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Figure 13. Detail of ventrites I–VI of females. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicate the proportions of ventrites V and VI." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758345" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758345/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 13</figureCitation>
(d)).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="218" pageId="27" pageNumber="217" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="27.[160,1156,732,1728]" box="[160,388,732,758]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,388,732,758]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Generic description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[160,1156,732,1728]" lastBlockId="28.[160,1156,142,861]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="218" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,243,767,792]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Length</emphasis>
: 
<quantity box="[256,415,767,792]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.745" metricValueMax="3.2299999999999995" metricValueMin="2.26" pageId="27" pageNumber="217" unit="mm" value="27.45" valueMax="32.3" valueMin="22.6">22.6–32.3 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[427,498,767,792]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Width</emphasis>
: 
<quantity box="[511,670,767,792]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2449999999999999" metricValueMax="1.41" metricValueMin="1.08" pageId="27" pageNumber="217" unit="mm" value="12.45" valueMax="14.1" valueMin="10.8">10.8–14.1 mm</quantity>
. Strong sexual dimorphism; body elongate, oval in dorsal view, subrectangular in lateral view; dorsal surface glabrous; ventral surface densely covered with yellow setae. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[556,634,837,862]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Colour</emphasis>
: Nearly completely black; protibiae sometimes dark reddish. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[318,380,871,896]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Head</emphasis>
: Slightly transverse (1.1 times wider than long). Clypeus triangular, acuminate and slightly reflexed anteriorly, surface finely punctate, glabrous. Frontoclypeal suture with a conical, short tubercle at middle. Frons glabrous, finely punctate at disc, smooth on a transverse area posteriorly; sides with large, deep, C-shaped, coalescent punctures. Ocular canthus transverse, subrectangular, rugopunctate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1008,1150,1010,1035]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Mouthparts</emphasis>
: Labrum transverse (3 times wider than long), parabola-shaped, transversely covered with a fringe of bristles posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[515,608,1079,1104]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="9.[160,225,1090,1113]" captionTargetBox="[166,1145,146,1050]" captionTargetId="figure-188@9.[166,1149,142,1058]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="Figure 6. Labrum in dorsal view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758331" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758331/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 6</figureCitation>
(e)). Mandibles with 2 teeth on outer margin (1 apical, 1 subapical) separated by a narrow notch; teeth slightly raised above clypeus laterally; apical tooth broadly truncated; subapical tooth rounded, clearly smaller compared to apical tooth (
<figureCitation box="[338,429,1183,1208]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="10.[160,225,1156,1179]" captionTargetBox="[169,1149,148,1090]" captionTargetId="figure-156@10.[166,1149,142,1125]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 7. Right mandible in dorsal view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicate the apical tooth in (a–e), striate molar in (d)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758333" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758333/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 7</figureCitation>
(e)). Maxillary galea transversely wider at middle than basis; outer margin rounded; inner margin with 6 teeth (3 apical, 2 medial, 1 basal); apical and medial teeth larger, scythe-shaped; basal tooth triangular, smaller than previous ones (
<figureCitation box="[1026,1115,1253,1278]" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="11.[160,225,1161,1184]" captionTargetBox="[167,1127,143,1126]" captionTargetId="figure-61@11.[166,1149,142,1129]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 8. Right maxilla in ventral view. (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Red arrows indicating triangular galea in (a), elongate maxillary palpomere II in (b), lobed inner margin of galea and stipe with triangular lobe in (c), pointed and triangular teeth on galea in (d), scythe-shape d teeth and rounded inner margin of galea in (e)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758335" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758335/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 8</figureCitation>
(e)). Maxillary palpomere II subequal in length to palpomere IV. Labium rounded laterally at basal half; apical half convergent towards a wide, truncated apex; surface densely surrounded with large, deep, bristled punctures; disc with scarce bristles. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[988,1103,1357,1382]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Antennae</emphasis>
: 10- segmented; club oval, subequal in length to antenomeres II–VII combined; scape clavate, densely setose. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[338,420,1426,1451]" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum, in dorsal view, with complete border, anteriorly with a forward produced horn at middle of anterior margin, posteriorly followed by a broad, deep, U-shaped concavity, reaching nearly to posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[859,950,1495,1520]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1146,1169]" captionTargetBox="[184,1146,142,1069]" captionTargetId="figure-59@12.[166,1149,142,1114]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 9. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of males in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii (Endrödi); (b) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (c) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (d) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758337" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758337/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="217">Figure 9</figureCitation>
(d)); in lateral view, pronotum strongly convex dorsally, with sinuous lateral margin, horn obliquely produced regarding antero-posterior body axis; discal surface of concavity covered with large, ocellate, irregularly scattered punctures; sides smooth, posterior area finely punctate. Scutellar plate subtriangular, irregularly punctate on anterior area, smooth posteriorly. Elytra with 10 well-marked longitudinal striae (1 sutural, 5 discal, 4 lateral); striae anteriorly covered with large, deep, oval punctures, becoming shallow towards posterior area; first interstria covered with large, ocellate, oval punctures; other interstriae finely punctate. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,214,177,202]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Legs</emphasis>
: Protarsi with sickle-shaped claws; protarsomere V subequal in length to tarsomeres II–IV combined; tarsomeres I–IV subequal in length. Protibiae with 4 short, triangular, as wide as long teeth on outer margins (
<figureCitation box="[589,682,246,271]" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="12.[160,225,1146,1169]" captionTargetBox="[184,1146,142,1069]" captionTargetId="figure-59@12.[166,1149,142,1114]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figure 9. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of males in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii (Endrödi); (b) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (c) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (d) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758337" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758337/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Figure 9</figureCitation>
(d)); teeth decreasing in size from basal to apical; dorsal surface with a longitudinal double row of bristled carinae. Mesofemora transverse, oval, densely setose. Mesotibiae with 2 carinae on outer surface (1 basal, 1 medial); apex truncated; medial carina and apex covered with stout, triangular spinules like setae. Metafemora wide compared to mesofemora; discal area glabrous, from smooth to finely punctate. Metatibiae similar to mesotibiae. Meso- and metatarsi similar in shape; tarsomeres I–IV decreasing in size; tarsomere V subequal in length to tarsomeres II–IV combined. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[287,403,489,514]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tergite VII coarsely rugopunctate, with no stridulatory apparatus. Tergite VIII strongly convex, completely, densely setose; sides rugose, disc finely punctate. Ventrites II–V subequal in length, rugopunctate, setose on sides; discal area glabrous, finely punctate; ventrite VI shorter compared to ventrite V, surface finely punctate, broadly emarginate posteriorly, covered with setae on posterior margin. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[864,943,628,653]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Venter</emphasis>
: Prosternal process triangular, densely punctate, setose. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[578,694,662,687]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Aedeagus</emphasis>
: Parameres, in dorsal view, symmetrical, finely punctate, subparallel, wide at basal half, narrow at middle, becoming wide at apical half, with scarce bristles scattered on inner margins (
<figureCitation box="[767,876,732,757]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="13.[160,226,1164,1187]" captionTargetBox="[169,1145,145,1132]" captionTargetId="figure-89@13.[166,1149,142,1133]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 10. Aedeagus with parameres in dorsal and lateral views, respectively. (a,b) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (c,d) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (e,f) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (g,h) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758339/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Figure 10</figureCitation>
(g)). Parameres, in lateral view, subequal in length to phallobasis, wide dorsoventrally at basal half, narrow dorsoventrally at apical half, slightly deflexed apically; ventral surface with a basal carina strongly produced downward (
<figureCitation box="[408,514,836,861]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="13.[160,226,1164,1187]" captionTargetBox="[169,1145,145,1132]" captionTargetId="figure-89@13.[166,1149,142,1133]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 10. Aedeagus with parameres in dorsal and lateral views, respectively. (a,b) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi; (c,d) Gibboryctes endroedii sp. nov.; (e,f) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (g,h) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758339" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758339/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Figure 10</figureCitation>
(h)).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[160,1156,920,1189]" box="[160,388,920,946]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,388,920,946]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Sexual dimorphism</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[160,1156,920,1189]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">
The female can be distinguished from the male in the following aspects: 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[996,1058,956,981]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Head</emphasis>
: Surface coarsely rugopunctate (
<figureCitation box="[428,534,990,1015]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="14.[160,225,1441,1464]" captionTargetBox="[168,1146,144,1407]" captionTargetId="figure-42@14.[166,1149,142,1410]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 11. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of females in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi;(b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedi sp.nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Arrow indicates punctate frons in (b)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758341" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758341/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Figure 11</figureCitation>
(e)); clypeus subtrapezoidal or subtriangular (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1155,990,1015]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="14.[160,225,1441,1464]" captionTargetBox="[168,1146,144,1407]" captionTargetId="figure-42@14.[166,1149,142,1410]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 11. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of females in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi;(b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedi sp.nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Arrow indicates punctate frons in (b)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758341" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758341/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Figure 11</figureCitation>
(e)). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[208,292,1025,1050]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum with no horn, only with 2 transverse, flattened tubercles adjacent to middle of anterior margin; anterior and concavity surfaces densely rugopunctate (
<figureCitation box="[168,273,1094,1119]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="14.[160,225,1441,1464]" captionTargetBox="[168,1146,144,1407]" captionTargetId="figure-42@14.[166,1149,142,1410]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 11. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of females in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi;(b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedi sp.nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Arrow indicates punctate frons in (b)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758341" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758341/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Figure 11</figureCitation>
(e)). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[325,380,1094,1119]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Legs</emphasis>
: Metafemora covered with well-marked, oval punctures. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1032,1149,1094,1119]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tergite VIII from flattened to slightly convex in lateral view. Ventrite V about 1.5 times longer than ventrite VI (
<figureCitation box="[430,535,1164,1189]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="14.[160,225,1441,1464]" captionTargetBox="[168,1146,144,1407]" captionTargetId="figure-42@14.[166,1149,142,1410]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 11. Detail of head, pronotum and prothoracic legs of females in dorsal view: (a) Gibboryctes szelenyii Endrödi;(b) Gibboryctes ebeninus sp. nov.; (c) Gibboryctes endroedi sp.nov.; (d) Heterogomphus gracilicornis Prell; (e) Tetragus waldenfelsi (Endrödi). Arrow indicates punctate frons in (b)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6758341" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6758341/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Figure 11</figureCitation>
(d)); ventrite VI with arched posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[160,1029,1248,1309]" box="[160,402,1248,1274]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,402,1248,1274]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">Specific composition</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[160,1029,1284,1309]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[160,1029,1248,1309]" box="[160,1029,1284,1309]" pageId="28" pageNumber="218">
